Data Visualization Project feat. Rstudio

A study of immigrants in Europe from 2011 to 2019

Our study is based on data from recent immigrants by gender, age and citizenship in European countries.

We are a dynamic duo data scientist team since...yesterday!

We explore data, we tell their story

Data have a story. They can't talk. We tell the story for them.

You may wonder about the name of the variable, why it is called thisPageData. On the website, there are several download options, we can choose between this page data, full data and source data. Weve downloaded all of the three. There are 343 lines in this page data, 1816 lines in full data and 27977 lines in source data. However all of the three have the same amount of countries : 38 countries.

At the beginning of the project, we are not very sure about our skill in R, so weve chosen the smallest. Weve found at the end of the project that this might be a bit too small.

As you can see, there are more than 10 columns in this data set. However, those who interest us are just three or four of them.

A little explanation about the data set :DATAFLOW is the intern reference of the database, which we dont try to understand.LAST UPDATE: as the name shows, its the last update time.FREQ: the time-frequency, A stands for annual.SEX: TRUE means it concludes both man and woman.geo: The abbreviation of the countries.value: number of immigrants, in the percentage of the total population.OBS_FLAG: comments about the value, there will be (b): break-in time series, (c): confidential and so on. In this study, we dont take care about it. For some further reasons which will be revealed later, weve added two columns, full_name, and region. The operation is done with Excel.

Barplot...and a small lineplot

1. Small line plot of
Luxembourg

We started with a simple graph, a line chart of Luxembourg. We chose Luxembourg randomly.

A line plot of the percentage of immigrants in the total population. For example, in the year 2011, people who immigrated to Luxembourg take 10.4% of the total populationof the country.

We can see that the percentage of the population increased between 2011 and 2012 and decrease between 2012 and 2013. After this, between 2013 and 2016, the percentage constantly increases and decreases slowly in 2017 and increase again between 2017 and 2019.

2. Circular barplot

Here, a circular barplot shows the different European countries classified by region, with the year, the value, and their full name. Its about the year 2019. We tried to find a way which can visualize all the countries at the same time, the solution is a circular barplot.

Right clic on the image to inspect a bigger one.

Now you can see why two new columns (full_name and region) are added in the source file. With the region column, we can group the countries according to theirgeographic region. With the full_name column, we dont need to search in Google what CH stands for. (You mightthink it means China, but in fact it means Switzerland.) Some countries dont appear because there is no value for the country.

4. Animation
circular barplot

A small problem with the previous barplot is that we can only show the case of one year, we cant inspect the evolution from 2011 to 2019. Another imperfection is the bar of Luxembourg is too tall, it makes the difference between others bars not obvious enough.

To make it better, we decided to make an animation from 2011 to 2019, without Luxembourg, so that we can cover all the years, with a clearer difference between the bars.


As we can see, this is a circular bar plot similar to the one we have already shown, but here the animated one shows the evolution of the population until the year 2020.

6. Comment animation
circular barplot

A few technical explanations:
The animation is made by the function transition_states, thanks to the package gganimate. transition_states means to make animation according to different states. In our case, the state is the year. The new column id2 that weve added is used for putting the animation in the right way.

Its really a pity that we havent been able to put a label which shows the year. We could have a try with transition_time and frame_time, however we have no longer time to spend on this.

Animation line plot

The animation of the circular barplot seems great, a further question appears: is barplot the best way to show an evolution? Why not simply a line plot? Thats why comes our next try.

anime_line<-thisPageData
p<-anime_line %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=year, y=value,group=geo,color=geo))+
  geom_line()+
  geom_point()+
  scale_color_viridis(discrete = TRUE)+
  ggtitle("Population of immigrants of BE, CH and LU")+
  theme_ipsum()+
  ylab("Percentage of total population")+
  scale_x_continuous("Year", breaks=anime_line$year, labels=anime_line$year )+
  transition_reveal(year)
p

What a mess. Weve succeeded to summon the Spaghetti plot of the legend. Obviously this is not a good chart.

The best solution to this issue is small multiple charts or a chart with interactivity. Limited by the time, we cannot step further to make these best solutions come true.

An alternative way is to control the number of lines under five, like the chart below.

anime_line<-thisPageData[c(which(thisPageData$geo=="LU"),which(thisPageData$geo=="BE"),which(thisPageData$geo=="CH")),]
p<-anime_line %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=year, y=value,group=geo,color=geo))+
  geom_line()+
  geom_point()+
  scale_color_viridis(discrete = TRUE)+
  ggtitle("Population of immigrants of BE, CH and LU")+
  theme_ipsum()+
  ylab("Percentage of total population")+
  scale_x_continuous("Year", breaks=anime_line$year, labels=anime_line$year )+
  transition_reveal(year)
p

Here we can see the evolution of the immigrant population of Belgium, Switzerland, and Luxembourg. The line for Luxembourg shows that the immigrant population increases between 2011 and 2019. In contrast to the line for Switzerland which shows a constant evolution after 2012. Finally, the Belgium line shows after a slight increase, a decrease in the immigrant population.

Circular barplot VS lineplot

We can conclude that with barplot, we can show every category of the study, which is impossible for alineplot. With a lineplot, we can show the evolution with time, which a barplot can hardly make.

Without labels, they have almost the same precision for visualization, as they all show the value by height or length.

The animation might be a good idea to combine their advantages. In this study, it seems that the barplot animation is better. (Only if there are labels and years on it.)

We cannot talk about geography without a map. Here is a choropleth showing the average value of immigration between 2011 and 2019.

Wondering where is the colorbar? Clic the righ arrow to continue.

Colorbar

100% homemade, no artificial ingrediants added.

In Matlab, a simple colorbar can make a colorbar. We havent found a similar function in R, so we managed to make a colorbar on our own with ggplot and geom_bar. We announce proudly tous nos ptes de colorbar sont fait la maison.

Technical explanation

This graph is not as easy as we thought.

Clic here for source code

We had a lot of difficulties with this plot. Firstly we found that in the first version, the map is made, but the color of each country doesnt match to its value. This is due to the disorder with our matrix and the matrix of the map that we download. This is solved by a combo of for, for, if.

Secondly, we inspected that almost half of the countries have no color. One reason is that the original value of the country is NA, we can do nothing with this. Another possibility is that the countries dont have the same abbreviation in our matrix and the matrix of the table. Thanks again to for, we found Greece (GR or EL) and Great Britain (GB or UK).

As Luxembourg has a value of 10 while the others have a value between 0 and 2, we can hardly distinguish the colors of countries with low values. In other word, the difference between color levels is not great enough. Nevermind, choropleth is not made for precision.

Explore the result

The data tells a story. All the charts want to tell THAT story, but from different points of view. The choropleth is the easiest one for visualization, so lets take it as an example.

A first glimpse of the map tells that, big countries like France, Italy, Spain have fewer immigrants, small countries like Luxembourg and Switzerland have much more immigrants.

However, the value is represented as the percentage of the total population. If we consider this, after a simple calculation, we get the number of immigrants of France is 67 000, and the one of Luxembourg is 63 000, they are at the same level. Meanwhile immigrants to China in 2012 are only 1202.

In a macroscopic view, the amount of immigrants in Europe is huge after 2011. To dig deeper, we must find external reasons in different fields. The biggest reason is the confluence of conflicts in parts of the Middle East, particularly the wars in Syria, Iraq, and Afghanistan. This leads to the European refugee crisis. Most of the European countries chose to accept refugees under certain conditions.

In a microscopic view, northern countries have a greater percentage of immigrants (and also Germany). This is due to the choice of refugees and the policy of each country.
